The bee car that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of the bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C that is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the Security Shield to four areas of Nissan.
This robot intends to strengthen the ability to prevent collisions of brand vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal space with oval shape that looks a lot like the Nissan Security Shield.
But the most important thing is the bee's composite eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing you to fly seamlessly within your own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles up to two metres away within a radius of 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to a micro-processor that immediately translates into collision prevention.
"At the moment you detect an obstacle, the small robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a straight or higher angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned upwards or downwards, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like the bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, for the small robot to avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with just a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about memory gigas, not even mega."
This is the first step to develop new technologies for instantaneous collision prevention, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced into serial cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles along the way.
