Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refound the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the common project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he is the third to vote on a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to the official results that referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28 %, 7 % of the votes cast were null and 0,7 % were blank.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls at the exit of the electoral centres and a count from a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory for the "yes", estimated at between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly " , he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who lead the Guayaquil government, 280 kilometres southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in full calm, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points consolidating the " new socialism " defended by the President.
The draft Constitution implies an increase in the power of the State over the economy, reserving it with the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially through the extraction of oil by foreign companies and through foreign exchange sending its emigrants.
Held by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the Head of State, who can make up to two consecutive terms of four years each and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that it would use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provided for the ban on the presence of foreign troops, which would put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 people abducted have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good when they arrived at 3:30 p.m. on board a special plane at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transported by helicopters to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they were unable to talk to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana declared at the airport.
On 19 September these hostages fell into the possession of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying a safari on all-terrain in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and since then have gone from one zule to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous travel agency, in charge of the safari organization.
An Egyptian security officer indicated that 30 members of the special forces, carried on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
" An exchange of fire took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled, " said the man who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the flash unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commanders.
The Italian Foreign Minister, Franco Frattini, mentioned in Belgrade the role played by the secret agents and by members of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men in the secret services, the special forces," he said without going into detail.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve of the day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an all-terrainer on which the kidnappers were on board, of which six were killed, including the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also stated that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by this group.
