The governments of the Netherlands are nationalizing a part of Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands states - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalisation to the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the American market: the three countries will support in total with 11,2 billion euros to this financial and insurance institution that also has business in Hungary.
This weekend, the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held higher-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission's head of economic competition.
The Fortis Bank is the first to suffer the Eurozone crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has occurred in several waves more than a year ago, so the decisions taken with respect to the Bank, in a sense, can be regarded as precedents.
According to the decision taken on Sunday morning, the three States will purchase approximately half (49 per cent) of the Bank's property in their area.
The Bank will surely sell part of its business, including mainly insurance activities purchased last year from the Dutch ABN Amró.
The actions of Fortis began a sharp decline last week and for the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree to point out that with its 85,000 employees this Bank is too large to allow it to break down.
The company's shares only decreased by 12 percent on Friday, being the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
Observing the current stock prices, the total value of the group's capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company's executives this is not real.
The Bank's management blamed the sudden fall of Fortis' shares on the insecurities of the US market in connection with the approval of the US package plan of $700 billion.
On Monday the shares showed a slight increase.
On Friday they appointed Filip Dierckx as the bank's new CEO.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured that investors did not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
Among the Bank's clients so far there was no panic, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
The Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
