The same must be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we trust the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, the designer of the prescription follow-up program.
Insurance companies make the insurance price and amount of compensation depend on the customer's state of health and if they believe that the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Before they sent the client to medical check and signed the contract with him already knowing the result of the check.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily gets from the pharmacies the list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the patient's illness and health status.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Many versions of the program circulate, some even set a number of risks, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has little to do, although there are small difficulties in this.
