The European Union doubles its trade with India
Since the European Union and India are reciprocally trading partners, this issue, in addition to the other largely global problems, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
While the European Union recognizes that India is a great democratic developing power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator as to whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue was not addressed at the ninth summit in Marseilles yesterday.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President-in-Office, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission and Javier Solana, the main representative of foreign policy, welcomed Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, that is to say, increase their trade to more than EUR 100 billion.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious target.
The 26 existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India were thus legally harmonized, so air transport can also fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union until the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up negotiations.
The objective is balance, because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among the trading partners of the Union.
The summit paid attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism - all forms of terrorism - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha round of trade liberalization was also urged, although both sides bear great responsibility for their failure.
The EU confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, i.e. until 2020 it wants to reduce pollutant emissions by at least 20 percent.
India also agrees with this, as at next year's climate conference, a global agreement should be reached and the production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 50 per cent by 2050.
They also wished to impede the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris trusts that French companies will be charged €20 billion to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency information the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
